sing, while the large majority of cities fail to do so? Invisible City calls for a brave new housing paradigm that makes the needs of marginalized populations visible to policy makers. Drawing on fascinating case studies in Houston, Louisville, and New Orleans, and analyzing census information as well as policy reports, Gilderbloom offers a comprehensive, engaging, and optimistic theory of how housing can be remade with a progressive vision. While many contemporary urban scholars have failed to capture the dynamics of what is happening in our cities, Gilderbloom presents a new vision of shelter as a force that shapes all residents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAppelbaum, Richard P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrazley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Michael Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHornburg, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLayman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehman, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Roger K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPan, Zhenfeng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeirce, Neal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoosa, Stephen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosentraub, Mark S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYe, Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71709140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.